\begin_layout Section
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Simply consider two objects floating in space with respective masses and
 known intial positions and velocities.
 These two bodies follow Newtons Law of graviatation.
 These will be our only assumptions (along with conservation of energy).
 Specifically we start by defining the force between two point paritcles
 in 3+1 flat euclian space with positions, velocities, and masses 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}(t)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}(t)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{x}_{1}(t)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{x}_{2}(t),M_{1},M_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Each particle exerts an equal and opposite force on each other along the
 vector 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 the line connecting the two particles .
 The force 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}$
\end_inset

denotes the force of particle 2 on 1, and vice versa for 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}$
\end_inset

 acts in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

 which we define as the vector pointing from 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}(t)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}(t)$
\end_inset

 (note we also define 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{r}$
\end_inset

to denote the unit vector where as 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 encodes the distant between the two particles as well as the direction).
 Formally,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
F_{1}=-G\frac{M_{1}M_{2}}{\Vert r(t)\Vert^{2}}\hat{r} & F_{2}=G\frac{M_{1}M_{2}}{\Vert r(t)\Vert^{2}}\hat{r}\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
r(t)=x_{1}(t)-x_{2}(t) & \hat{r}=\frac{x_{1}(t)-x_{2}(t)}{\Vert x_{1}(t)-x_{2}(t)\Vert}\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Applying netwons second law (
\begin_inset Formula $F=m\ddot{x}$
\end_inset

) to this yields the following highly non linear ODE:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\ddot{x}_{1}=-G\frac{M_{2}}{\Vert r(t)\Vert^{2}}\hat{r} & \ddot{x}_{2}=G\frac{M_{1}}{\Vert r(t)\Vert^{2}}\hat{r}\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

