\begin_layout Section
Center of Mass, Reduction to 1-D Problem, and Linear Momentum Conserved
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3) Is very compact and intuitive but is highly non linear and does imediatly
 suggest a solution.
 So we know the center of mass is an important point in gravitation problems
 so lets see the dynamics of the center of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{com}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 By definition 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{com}(t)=\frac{1}{M_{1}+M_{2}}(M_{1}x_{1}(t)+M_{2}x_{2}(t))$
\end_inset

.
 Now simply differentiate twice with respect to time:
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{x}_{com}(t)=\frac{\Vert r(t)\Vert^{2}}{M_{1}+M_{2}}(F_{1}+F_{2})=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}=-F_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus we can see that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{com}(t)$
\end_inset

 is non accelerating and thus is an interial frame and so we will continue
 our analysis in this frame.
 As a quick detour, this allows us to show that momentum is conserved.
 To see this, consider that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{x}_{com}(t)$
\end_inset

 is constant by the above reasoning.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{x}_{com}(t)=\frac{1}{M_{1}+M_{2}}(p_{1}(t)+p_{2}(t))$
\end_inset

 is constant implying the total momentum is constant.
 Now continuing, we can rewrite 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}(t)$
\end_inset

 in terms of the center of mass.
 Foreshadowing, lets define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\frac{M_{1}M_{2}}{M_{1}+M_{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{com}(t)=\frac{\mu}{M_{2}}x_{1}(t)+\frac{\mu}{M_{1}}x_{2}(t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{1}(t)=\frac{\mu}{M_{2}}x_{1}(t)+\frac{\mu}{M_{1}}x_{2}(t)-\frac{\mu}{M_{1}}x_{2}(t)-(\frac{\mu}{M_{2}}-1)x_{1}(t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{1}(t)=x_{com}(t)-(\frac{\mu}{M_{1}}x_{2}(t)+\frac{-M_{2}}{M_{1}+M_{2}}x_{1}(t))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally we get the following, where the posistion of particle 2 comes from
 symmetry:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
x_{1}(t)=x_{com}(t)+\frac{\mu}{M_{1}}r(t) & x_{2}(t)=x_{com}(t)-\frac{\mu}{M_{2}}r(t)\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Selecting the center of mass as our interial frame shows 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}(t)$
\end_inset

 only depend on the vector defining their displacement 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

.
 So what are the dynamics of 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

? Well first 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ddot{r}(t)=\ddot{x}_{1}(t)-\ddot{x}_{2}(t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aplying (3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ddot{r}=-G\frac{M_{2}}{\Vert r(t)\Vert^{2}}-G\frac{M_{1}}{\Vert r(t)\Vert^{2}}\hat{r}=-(M_{1}+M_{2})\frac{G}{\Vert r(t)\Vert^{2}}\hat{r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A little maniputlation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{M_{1}M_{2}}{M_{1}+M_{2}}\ddot{r}=F_{1}=-G\frac{M_{1}M_{2}}{\Vert r(t)\Vert^{2}}\hat{r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cleaning up
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu\ddot{r}=F_{1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So we see that our two particle system can be broken into a simplier one
 body problem, whosw position is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

, with mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\frac{M_{1}M_{2}}{M_{1}+M_{2}}$
\end_inset

, subject to a net force 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}.$
\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}$
\end_inset

points in the opposite direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

, impling the force is trying to pull the bodies together as expected, but
 the pull weakens as 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

 increases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Angular Momentum is Conserved and Reduction to 2+1 Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lets looks at the angular momentum of this 1 particle system.
 
\begin_inset Formula $L=r\times p=r\times\mu\dot{r}.$
\end_inset

 Now simply take the time derivative this expression.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{L}=(\dot{r}\times\mu\dot{r})+(r\times\mu\ddot{r})$
\end_inset

.
 Now the first term is 0, because the cross product of a vector and its
 scalar multiple is zero.
 Now the second term is just 
\begin_inset Formula $r\times\mu\ddot{r}=r\times F_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 These two vectors are anti parallel by defintion and this is 0.
 This implies the rate at which angular momentum is changing is zero.
 This implies angular momentum is constant.
 So we let 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 be the intial and only angular momentum of this system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With angular momentum being conserved, we can find an interial frame where
 are 1 particle system rotates in a 2D plane.
 So from here on out we will assume that we are in that we are in that interial
 frame and will assume the third component of our 3D system is 0.
 So, 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)=r_{x}(t)\hat{i}+r_{y}(t)\hat{j}$
\end_inset

 in the 2D cartesian coordinate plane.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Energy and Polar Coordinates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let us look at the energy of this, 2D 1 body problem.
 The total energy is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $E=K+U$
\end_inset

.
 Where 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\frac{1}{2}\mu\Vert\dot{r}\Vert^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U=-G\frac{M_{1}M_{2}}{\Vert r(t)\Vert}$
\end_inset

.
 So before continuing let us define polar cordinates.
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{y}(t)=R(t)\sin(\theta(t))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{x}=R(t)\cos(\theta(t))$
\end_inset

.
 This is motivated by the fact that our problem now exists in the catesian
 plane, and we know that these equations describe graviataion and thus usually
 exhibit an orbitting behavior.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $U(R)=-G\frac{M_{1}M_{2}}{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Now finding the kinetic energy is a bit more complicated, but we have the
 following transformation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{r}_{x}=\dot{R}\cos(\theta)-R\sin(\theta)\dot{\theta}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{r}_{y}=\dot{R}\sin(\theta)+R\cos(\theta)\dot{\theta}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So we already have our potentail energy in terms of our new polar coordinate
 variables, 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,\theta)$
\end_inset

.
 Now let us find an expression in these coordinates for our kinetic energy.
 We know 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\frac{1}{2}\mu(\dot{r}_{x}^{2}+\dot{r}_{y}^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 We can plug our transformation from above into this expression and one
 gets:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K=\frac{1}{2}\mu(\dot{R}^{2}+R^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However we can simplify this further.
 Since we know that angular momentum is constant, we can rewrite the angular
 velocity term above using this constant.
 We know 
\begin_inset Formula $L=I\dot{\theta}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\mu R^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the moment of inertia.
 Solving this for the angular velocity leads to 
\begin_inset Formula $w=\dot{\theta}=\frac{L}{\mu R^{2}}$
\end_inset

 .
 Pluging this into kinetic energy gives: 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\frac{1}{2}\mu\dot{R}^{2}+\frac{L^{2}}{2\mu R^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 So we get an expression for the total energy of this system 
\begin_inset Formula $E=K+U$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E=\frac{1}{2}\mu\dot{R}^{2}+\frac{L^{2}}{2\mu R^{2}}-G\frac{M_{1}M_{2}}{R}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the next section we show how to solve this using conservation of energy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve (5) we must assume that energy is conserved and thus total energy
 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is constant.
 It would nice to derive this from the defintion of the forces acting our
 system, and it possibly falls out from the fact that the force is conservative,
 but its simply easier to assume its conserved and move on.
 So we take the time derivative of (5) and get the following differential
 equations (we also include the dynamics of the angular velocity as the
 below will now fully describe the time depedant dynamics of our system):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\frac{dE}{dt}=\mu\ddot{R}-\frac{L^{2}}{\mu R^{3}}+G\frac{M_{1}M_{2}}{R^{2}}=0 & w=\dot{\theta}=\frac{l}{\mu R^{2}}\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a system of non-linear second order differential equationa and thus
 we will need to play with it a bit to solve it.
 The above is a time depedant equation, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R=R(t)$
\end_inset

.
 We can simplyify the above by using the angular velocity to find a single
 time indepandt differential equation.
 So, we can do a change of variables as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\theta}{dt}=\frac{L}{\mu R^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dR}{dt}=\frac{dR}{d\theta}\frac{d\theta}{dt}=\frac{dR}{d\theta}\frac{L}{\mu R^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}R}{dt^{2}}=(\frac{d}{dt}\frac{dR}{d\theta})\frac{d\theta}{dt}+\frac{dR}{d\theta}(\frac{d^{2}\theta}{dt^{2}})=(\frac{d^{2}R}{d\theta^{2}})(\frac{L}{\mu R^{2}})^{2}+(\frac{dR}{d\theta})^{2}\frac{-2L}{\mu R^{3}}\frac{L}{\mu R^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can subsitute in the above into (6) giving us a time indepedant different
ial equation describing our system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d^{2}R}{d\theta^{2}}\frac{1}{R^{2}}-(\frac{dR}{d\theta})^{2}\frac{2}{R^{3}}-\frac{1}{R}+\mu\frac{GM_{1}M_{2}}{L^{2}}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now lets try the subsitution 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\frac{1}{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dR}{d\theta}=-\frac{1}{u^{2}}\frac{du}{d\theta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{2}R}{d\theta^{2}}=\frac{2}{u^{3}}\frac{du}{d\theta}-\frac{1}{u^{2}}\frac{d^{2}u}{d\theta^{2}}$
\end_inset

 .
 Plugging this subsittion into our time indepedant equation gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}u}{d\theta^{2}}=\mu\frac{GM_{1}M_{2}}{L^{2}}-u
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can easily solve this.
 To make that apparent we let 
\begin_inset Formula $v=u-\mu\frac{GM_{1}M_{2}}{L^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Which gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}v}{d\theta^{2}}=-v
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This has solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $v=c_{1}\sin(\theta)+c_{2}\cos(\theta)$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\frac{1}{R}=c_{1}\sin(\theta)+c_{2}\cos(\theta)+\mu\frac{GM_{1}M_{2}}{L^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Now we can choose our coordinates so that the sin term goes away.
 This yields the following explicit soltion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R=\frac{L^{2}}{\mu GM_{1}M_{2}}\frac{1}{1+e\cos(\theta)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Keep in mind we still have have the following relation 
\begin_inset Formula $w=\dot{\theta}=\frac{L}{\mu R^{2}}$
\end_inset

 which allows us to convert from the angular domain to the time domain.
 But as we can see from (8) the general geometry of the solution is that
 off conic sections.
 Thus the possible set of solutions is a cirlce, ellipse, parabola, or hyberbola
 (and possibly others).
 For a given set of initial conditions, determining which set the dynamics
 fall into is simply a matter of finding the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 in (8).
 Now we can plug the radius above into the formulas for Kinetic Energy,
 Total energy, and angular velocity so that we have a set of equations that
 sufficently describe the dynamics of our two body and reduced 1 body system.
 These are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Radial:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\frac{L^{2}}{\mu GM_{1}M_{2}}\frac{1}{1+e\cos(\theta)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Energy:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K=\frac{1}{2}\mu\dot{R}^{2}+\frac{L^{2}}{2\mu R^{2}}=\frac{\mu G^{2}M_{1}^{2}M_{2}^{2}}{2L^{2}}(e^{2}+1+2e\cos(\theta))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E=K+U=\frac{\mu G^{2}M_{1}^{2}M_{2}^{2}}{L^{2}}(\frac{e^{2}-1}{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Angular:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w=\frac{L}{\mu R^{2}}=\frac{\mu G^{2}M_{1}^{2}M_{2}^{2}}{L^{3}}(1+e\cos(\theta))^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Time:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t(\theta)=\frac{L^{3}}{\mu G^{2}M_{1}^{2}M_{2}^{2}}\intop_{0}^{\theta}\frac{ds}{(1+e\cos(s))^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above fully describe the dynamics of our system.
 For a given angle we can describe the radius, angular velocity, and kinetic
 energy.
 If one is interested in answering questions such as how long it takes to
 do X or at what point will X happen, then one can use numeric integration
 to calculate how long it takes to sweep a certain angle and use the other
 formulas to compute the desired quantity.
 The total energy, and thus the eccentricity of the orbit is determined
 by the initial conditions.
 As well as the angular momentum.
\end_layout

